Topic

Internet use based on respondents characteristics (age, education, happiness).

Country

Finland

Variables choice & hypotheses

Background & hypotheses

Outcome variable - Internet use on a typical day in minutes

  1. Our first research hypothesis is based on the relationship between Internet use and age - we assume that children and the elderly will use the Internet less than young and middle-aged people. In this hypothesis we expect a negative correlation with outliers starting around age 50, hence the correlation in this case will be of medium strength. This hypothesis is based on the report we found [1], where authors state that older adults do not use the Internet very frequently - Internet usage is much less prevalent among members of the G.I. Generation (adults who are currently 76 and older) than among other age groups.

  2. The second research hypothesis is about the dependence of the Internet use on an education a person has. We assume that more educated people are from higher classes with greater access to the Internet, moreover, they are more advanced Internet users. Here we can also mention that the Internet is used for education, so the longer you study, the more you use it. Therefore, here we expect to observe a positive correlation of small to moderate strength. In one of the researches [2] we found that the percentages of people with internet access grew primarily in the middle and older age groups between 2002 and 2014. Furthermore, being male and having a higher education were both associated with greater odds of internet access. <> Finally, both greater income and cognitive ability were associated with greater odds of internet access, while providing care for a grandchild was significantly associated with internet access only among the oldest age group.

  3. Our third hypothesis is about the dependence of Internet use on happiness. We assume that unhappy people can use internet resources for escapism (i.e.to cope with unhappiness) or to help themselves, and happy people do not use it that much because they do not need to escape from unpleasant reality. Here we expect a small to medium strength negative correlation. This hypothesis is based on the information we gathered - a work [3] where authors state that The present data imply that heavier computer users are not so much disinhibited or stimulus seeking, but have a poorer self-esteem. Whether the poorer self-esteem leads to greater computer use, or prolonged time on the Internet leads to problems that affect self-worth is not clear.. As there is no self-esteem variable in ESS dataset we have chosen happiness level as those two seem similar.

  4. Our fourth hypothesis includes a categorical variable, but it is similar to the one in the 2nd hypothesis - education level of the respondent. As those variables virtually correspond to the same concept, we expect to see similar correlation as in the second hypothesis.

Plots & descriptives for variables

Now that we have recoded and renamed each variable (again, for convenience), we can build plots to see how they are distributed.

Numeric variables

Lets start with histograms for numeric variables. We need to assess their normality before performing correlation tests, as based on that (and other assumptions) we will choose the appropriate method.

ggplot(ESS3, aes(x=netusemin)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=20, color="black", fill="#fdbcb4")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(netustm)), color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  theme_minimal()

  • netusemin - internet usage per day in minutes, outcome variable, ratio:
  • here we see that the variable is severely right-skewed, so most people tend to spend less than 400-500 min a day on the internet; the distribution is unimodal and somewhat bell-shaped; it is far from normal.
ggplot(ESS3, aes(x=age)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=25,color="black", fill="#87CEEB")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(agea)), color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  theme_minimal()

  • age - calculated age of respondents, full years, ratio:
  • this variable is also unimodal, but we cannot say that it is bell-shaped or normal; the researchers seemed to collect respondents of different age groups, so there is a similar amount of most ages.
ggplot(ESS3, aes(x=eduyrs_n)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 50,color="black", fill="#87CEEB")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(eduyrs)), color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  theme_minimal()

  • eduyrs_n - sum of years spent on education, full years, ratio:
  • this distribution is unimodal and bell-shaped, but is right-skewed because of several outliers (people who spent over 30 years on education); again, it is not normal.
ggplot(ESS3, aes(x=happylvl)) + 
  geom_histogram(breaks = seq(0, 11, by=1),color="black", fill="#87CEEB")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(happy)), color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  theme_minimal()

  • happylvl - self-assessed level of happiness of respondents, quasi-interval:
  • this variables distribution is left-skewed, unimodal and close to bell-shaped; most respondents seem to indicate quite high levels of happiness (7 and higher).

Correlation

Before performing correlation test, we need to decide which method to use - parametric Pearsons test or non-parametric Spearmans or Kendalls. For that, we need to check several assumptions of Pearsons correlation test:

  • linearity
  • outliers
  • homoscedasticity
  • normality

Linearity + Outliers + Homoscedasticity

ggplot(ESS3, aes(x = age, y = netusemin)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, position = "jitter") +
  geom_smooth()

As we can see, the relationship netusemin ~ age is hardly linear. Even though we see that the line shows some kind of pattern, if we look at the data points themselves, it is far from obvious and there are a lot of outliers. Thus, it is non-linear relationships with significant outliers. Severe heteroscedasticity is also visible.

ggplot(ESS3, aes(x = eduyrs_n, y= netusemin)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, position = "jitter")+
  geom_smooth(color = "red")

Even though the outliers are not so visible, netusemin ~ eduyrs_n relationship is non-linear, since the data points are clustered together. It is hard to estimate homoscedasticity here, since there is no visible line.

ggplot(ESS3, aes(x = happylvl, y= netusemin)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, position = "jitter")+
  geom_smooth(color = "green")

netusemin ~ happylvl relationship is hardly linear too. The data points are clustered together, even though there are some noticable outliers. Again, it is hard to estimate homoscedasticity here, since there is no visible line.

Linearity + Outliers conclusion

The relationships between chosen variables are either close to non-linear or non-linear, the outliers are significantly noticable in 2 of the graphs. The homoscedasticity is either hard to estimate or not present. Thus, our variables do not pass the linearity, outliers and homoscedasticity assumptions.

Normality assumption

Lets check the normality of each variables distributions:

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(ESS3_1$netusemin) 
hist(ESS3_1$age) 
hist(ESS3_1$eduyrs_n)
hist(ESS3_1$happylvl)

As we can see, Internet use, education years and happiness level are visibly not normal, which is confirmed by their skewness. In case of age, it is different from the rest of the distributions, but still seems not normal due to its non-bell shape. However, since for Pearsons correlation test we need to satisfy univariate normality in both variables in the relationship, and Internet use variable, to which we are going to compare age, is not normal already, we can dismiss this issue.

Normality conclusion

3 out of 4 variables are not normal. The one that is can seemingly be close to being normally distributed is in pair with a not normal variable, which does not satisfy the univariate normality requirement.

All assumptions conclusion

Our variables did not pass any of requirements for the Pearsons correlation test, so we decided to use Spearmans test instead.

Correlation tests

Before running the Spearmans correlation test, lets spell out statistical hypotheses.

H0: there is no monotonic relationship between the two variables in the population (rho is equal to 0)

H1: there is a monotonic relationship between the two variables in the population (rho is not equal to 0)

cor.test(ESS3_1$age, ESS3_1$netusemin, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  ESS3_1$age and ESS3_1$netusemin
## S = 760994237, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##        rho 
## -0.4432935

First of all, the p-value is very small, so there is a connection between those variables. In addition, rho is not equal to zero. Thus, we should reject the null hypothesis for those variables.

cor.test(ESS3_1$eduyrs_n, ESS3_1$netusemin, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  ESS3_1$eduyrs_n and ESS3_1$netusemin
## S = 423852629, p-value = 1.591e-13
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.1911771

Again, small p-value - presence of connection. Rho is not equal to zero, so we should reject the null hypothesis for these variables too.

cor.test(ESS3_1$happylvl, ESS3_1$netusemin, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  ESS3_1$happylvl and ESS3_1$netusemin
## S = 555202419, p-value = 0.04235
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##         rho 
## -0.05299094

P-value is small, rho is not equal to zero - we should reject the null hypothesis.

Boxplot for categorical predictor

ggplot(ESS3_2, aes(x=edlvl, y = netusemin)) +
  geom_boxplot()

For all groups, medians are within the range of 1st and 3rd quartiles. So there is no statiscally significant difference in Internet use between respondents with different education levels.

People with higher education (BA and MA or higher) seem to have bigger variances in Internet use, i.e.the differences between 1st and 3rd quartiles in their case are bigger. Also, their 3rd and 4th quartiles are higher than in the rest of the groups, so we can suppose that respondents with higher education may show higher rates of Internet use, but still not statistically significant from others.

People with lower levels of education seem to have more noticable outliers.

Comparing model fits

To assess model fit we should look at R^2 and R^2 adjusted - they show the relation of variance explained by the model to total variance of the outcome variable. We can assume that R^2 >= 0.1 shows a satisfactory level of the predictive power our model holds. Also, the higher the R^2 (the closer to 1 or 100%) the better for us.

  • model 1: R^2 / R^2 adjusted is 0.124 / 0.124 - it is higher than 0.1 and there is no difference - between two values of R^2
  • model 2: R^2 / R^2 adjusted is 0.159 / 0.158 - it is higher than 0.1 and there is a small (0.001) difference between two values of R^2
  • model 3: R^2 / R^2 adjusted is 0.160 / 0.158 - it is higher than 0.1 and there is a slightly higher difference (0.002 compared to 0 and 0.001 in model 1 and model 2 respectively) between two values of R^2
  • model 4: R^2 / R^2 adjusted is 0.168 / 0.164 - it is higher than 0.1 and there is a higher difference (0.004 compared to 0, 0.001 and 0.002 in model 1, model 2 and model 3 respectively) between two values of R^2

Choosing the best model & assessing model fit

We can further consider model 4, as it has the highest rate of variance explained (R^2). R^2 / R^2 adjusted is bigger than 0.1 (0.168 - so about 17% of variance in our sample is explained by that model; in contrast, other models have lower rate of explanation of variance: model 1 - 12%, model 2 - 16%, model 3 - 16%). Also, p-values of most predictors show statistically significant results. Finally, there is a small difference between R^2 and R^2 adjusted, meaning that even if we take into account the sample size and number of predictors, our rate of explaining the variance would not change drastically (the difference is only 0.004 or 0.04% which is not much).

Intercept is at point 293.90. This means that the person of 0 age, with 0 years of education, 0 happiness level and a lower secondary or less level of education will use internet for 294 (rounded) minutes a day (or about 5 hours).

Now lets consider the estimates of predictors:

  • Age of respondent:

    • the slope is negative (-3.13)
    • the relationship is statistically significant as we have a very small (<0.001) p-value
    • the slope strength is rather weak since the decrease of 3 minutes between ages within 1 year difference seems not so big;

  • Years of full-time education completed:

    • the slope is positive (4.86)
    • the relationship is statistically significant as we have a very small (<0.001) p-value
    • the slope strength is rather weak, just like in the previous case;

  • Happiness level:

    • the slope is negative (-4.22)
    • the relationship is not statistically significant as we have a p-value bigger than 0.05 (0.151)
    • the slope strength is weak, just like in the previous cases;

  • Education level: it is a dummy variable and category advanced vocational is seen as a baseline. So, in relation to it:

    • level BA:

    • has a positive slope (30.13)

    • this relationship is statistically significant (p-value is 0.023 < 0.05)

    • the slope also shows a stronger relationship than previous cases (the change in internet use between categories is about half an hour a day)

    • level lower secondary or less:

    • has a positive slope (7.36)

    • its strength is rather small

    • there is no statistically significant relationship (p-value is 0.632 > 0.05)

    • level MA or higher:

    • has a positive slope (29.70)

    • this relationship is statistically significant (p-value is 0.016 < 0.05)

    • the slope indicates a somewhat strong relationship (the change in internet use between categories is about half an hour a day)

    • level upper secondary:

    • has a negative slope (-11.86)

    • slopes strength seems weaker than in the previous categories

    • and this relationship is statistically insignificant (p-value is 0.310 > 0.05).

Regression equation

The regression equation consists of intercept estimate and each predictors estimates.

Our variables that will describe our regression equation:

  • y - Internet use on a typical day, in minutes (outcome variable);

  • a - Age of respondent, calculated;

  • b - Years of full-time education completed;

  • c - whether the person is at a BA level of education (dummy variable);

  • d - whether the person is at a MA or higher level of education (dummy variable);

  • intercept that is equal to 293.90.

The equation in our case will be the following:

y = 293.90 - 3.13 * a + 4.86 * b + 30.13 * c + 29.70 * d

Conclusion for the output table & overall project

The model only with significant predictors includes Age of respondent, Years of education, Education level.

  • There is a negative connection between the Age of respondent and Internet use (-3.16), i.e.the Internet use slightly decreases (by ~ 3 minutes a day) as respondents get older

  • this is coherent with our initial hypothesis.

  • The connection between Years of education and Internet use is positive and also rather weak (4.93), i.e.the Internet use increases with each year respondent spent on education by approximately 5 minutes a day

  • this is coherent with our initial hypothesis.

  • The Education level predicts Internet use only in cases when the respondents have a higher education (BA, MA or higher); in those cases the connection is positive and rather strong, i.e.in both cases the internet use is higher by ~30 minutes a day than in the baseline case (advanced vocational)

  • this is partly in line with our initial hypothesis as we expected people with higher education to use Internet more than with any other level of education and here we can see that this is true at least in comparison with one of the categories.

The Happiness level did not show statistically significant relationship with Internet use in case of regression model, so we can say that our initial hypothesis about this predictor was refuted. However, the correlation was significant but small.
